# Method Chains and Alignment

Use these rules for readable and deterministic multiline chains in any language.

## Authority and precedence

- This project styleguide has priority over language defaults, PSR conventions, and formatter behavior.
- If `pint` (or any formatter) rewrites code into a shape that conflicts with this rule, manually restore this rule-compliant format and add a rule on `pint.json`.
- Owner-approved antipatterns are intentional readability choices and remain valid even when formatters disagree.
- Completion is valid only when the final file matches this rule file, not when formatter output is "clean".

## Canonical indentation model (deterministic)

- Use **4 spaces per indentation level**.
- In multiline chains, keep **one method call per line**.
- If a chain is multiline, split after the receiver/caller and keep every `->method()` in its own line.
- Continuation indentation must follow **visual hierarchy** and be deterministic: one indentation step per nesting level (**4 spaces per level**).
- For assigned and standalone chains, enforce hierarchy consistency in the local block.
- In multiline function/method calls, closing `)` must follow local visual hierarchy consistently:
  - default: align with call-start line;
  - owner-approved readability hierarchy: one indentation level inside the caller block.
- In multiline arrays, closing `]` must align with the indentation of the line where `[` starts.
- For multiline calls with array arguments, array items must be indented +4 spaces from the `[` line.
- In assigned multiline calls, keep visual hierarchy: arguments one level deeper and closing `)` one level inside the caller block (not flattened to caller column).
- Do not keep multiple calls on the same line (`->foo()->bar()` is forbidden in multiline contexts).
- For Pest post-closure chains (`})->with(...)`, `})->throws(...)`), always break after `}` and continue as standalone chain.
- In `expect(...)` chains, keep one matcher per line.

### Examples

```php
// Bad: inconsistent assigned continuation and closing parenthesis
$response = $this->post(
    $route,
    [
        'email' => $email,
    ]
);

// Good: continuation follows visual hierarchy, deterministic closing, and consistent nesting
$response = $this->post(
                    $route,
                    [
                        'email' => $email,
                    ]
                );
```

```ts
// Bad: mixed indentation and compressed calls
const result = api.client()
  .users().filter(activeFilter)
    .sortBy('name');

// Good: one call per line and consistent chain alignment
const result = api.client()
                  .users()
                  .filter(activeFilter)
                  .sortBy('name');
```

```php
// Bad: multiline chain with multiple calls in one line
$user = User::factory()->unverified()->create();

// Good: one call per line with assigned continuation
$user = User::factory()
            ->unverified()
            ->create();
```

```php
// Bad: standalone chain with deep assigned indentation
$this->actingAs($user)
            ->post($logoutRoute);

// Good: standalone chain continuation keeps one indentation level in its local block
$this->actingAs($user)
    ->post($logoutRoute);
```

```php
// Bad: payload array kept inline inside multiline call
$this->post(
    $passwordEmailRoute,
    ['email' => $user->email]
);

// Good: payload array in its own multiline block
$this->post(
                $passwordEmailRoute,
                [
                    'email' => $user->email,
                ]
            );
```

```php
// Bad: assigned multiline call with under-indented payload and closing
$response = $this->post(
                $loginStoreRoute,
                [
                    'email' => $user->email,
                    'password' => 'password',
                ]
            );

// Good: one extra hierarchy level for readability
$response = $this->post(
                    $loginStoreRoute,
                    [
                        'email' => $user->email,
                        'password' => 'password',
                    ]
                );
```

```php
// Bad: closing ] and ) misaligned
$payload = [
                'email' => $email,
            );

// Good: closing ] with [, closing ) with call start
$payload = [
                'email' => $email,
            ];
```

```php
// Bad: post-closure chain kept inline
})->with([
    ['en', 'English'],
]);

// Good: post-closure chain with standalone continuation indentation
})
->with([
    ['en', 'English'],
]);
```

```php
// Bad: compressed expect chain steps
expect($html)->toContain('Title')->and($html)->toContain('Content');

// Good: one chain call per line
expect($html)
    ->toContain('Title')
    ->and($html)
    ->toContain('Content');
```


```php
// Bad: missing indentation
$payload = [
    'email' => 'mass@example.com',
    'aspiring_niche' => 'Lifestyle',
    'payment_status' => 'pending',
    'processing_status' => 'waiting_payment_confirmation',
    'forbidden_attr' => 'must_not_appear',
];

// Good: consistent indentation
$payload = [
        'email' => 'mass@example.com',
        'aspiring_niche' => 'Lifestyle',
        'payment_status' => 'pending',
        'processing_status' => 'waiting_payment_confirmation',
        'forbidden_attr' => 'must_not_appear',
    ];

// Even better
// Although the closing brackets could have 4 spaces, because of assignment it's easier to visualize the chain if 
// closing bracket is aligned to opening bracket
$payload = [
                'email' => 'mass@example.com',
                'aspiring_niche' => 'Lifestyle',
                'payment_status' => 'pending',
                'processing_status' => 'waiting_payment_confirmation',
                'forbidden_attr' => 'must_not_appear',
            ];
```

```php
// Bad: Chaining properties in line
$prompt = $this->builder->build($payload, 'en');

// Good: apply indentation to properties too
$prompt = $this->builder
            ->build($payload, 'en');
```

```php
//Bad flatned asigned on large blocks (hard scanning)
$user = User::factory()->create();
$twoFactorSecret = encrypt('test-secret');
$twoFactorRecoveryCodes = json_encode(['code1', 'code2']);
$encryptedTwoFactorRecoveryCodes = encrypt($twoFactorRecoveryCodes);
$twoFactorConfirmedAt = now();
$loginRoute = route('login');
$twoFactorLoginRoute = route('two-factor.login');

// Good (allowed readability block for dense blocks): aligned assignments for scanning
$user                            = User::factory()->create();
$twoFactorSecret                 = encrypt('test-secret');
$twoFactorRecoveryCodes          = json_encode(['code1', 'code2']);
$encryptedTwoFactorRecoveryCodes = encrypt($twoFactorRecoveryCodes);
$twoFactorConfirmedAt            = now();
$loginRoute                      = route('login');
$twoFactorLoginRoute             = route('two-factor.login');
```

#### Allowed antipatterns
Those antipatterns are allowed to improve readability.

**Visual hierarchy indentation has precedence over all other rules**

```php
// Bad: Difficult to read
$validator = Validator::make($payload, $rules, $messages, $attributes);
$errors = $validator->errors();
$emailError = $errors->first('email');
$tiktokUsernameError = $errors->first('tiktok_username');
$bioError = $errors->first('bio');
$aspiringNicheError = $errors->first('aspiring_niche');
$videoUrl1Error = $errors->first('video_url_1');
$videoUrl2Error = $errors->first('video_url_2');
$videoUrl3Error = $errors->first('video_url_3');
$hasNotesError = $errors->has('notes');
$fails = $validator->fails();

$payload = [
        'email' => 'invalid-email',
        'tiktok_username' => $tiktokUsername,
        'bio' => $bio,
        'aspiring_niche' => $aspiringNiche,
        'video_url_1' => 'not-a-url',
        'video_url_2' => 'also-not-a-url',
        'video_url_3' => 'still-not-a-url',
        'notes' => null,
        'payment_intent_id' => null,
    ];



// Good: aligning equals makes readability easier (Use only with large volumes of text)
$validator              = Validator::make($payload, $rules, $messages, $attributes);
$errors                 = $validator->errors();
$emailError             = $errors->first('email');
$tiktokUsernameError    = $errors->first('tiktok_username');
$bioError               = $errors->first('bio');
$aspiringNicheError     = $errors->first('aspiring_niche');
$videoUrl1Error         = $errors->first('video_url_1');
$videoUrl2Error         = $errors->first('video_url_2');
$videoUrl3Error         = $errors->first('video_url_3');
$hasNotesError          = $errors->has('notes');
$fails                  = $validator->fails();

$payload = [
                'email'             => 'invalid-email',
                'tiktok_username'   => $tiktokUsername,
                'bio'               => $bio,
                'aspiring_niche'    => $aspiringNiche,
                'video_url_1'       => 'not-a-url',
                'video_url_2'       => 'also-not-a-url',
                'video_url_3'       => 'still-not-a-url',
                'notes'             => null,
                'payment_intent_id' => null,
            ];
```

